ary Systems Biology research. Icahn School of Medicine at Mount Sinai'),(227,'Introduction to Tissue Engineering',NULL,NULL,'Coursera','Biology & Life Sciences',' Introduction to Tissue Engineering Coursera Biology & Life Sciences Dr. Yaakov Nahmias Step into the world of Tissue Engineering, a rapidly expanding field of applied biology aiming to create artificial organs for transplantation, basic research, or drug development. Hebrew University of Jerusalem'),(228,'Climate Change',NULL,NULL,'Coursera','Economics & Finance',' Climate Change Coursera Economics & Finance Prof Jon Barnett Prof John Freebairn Prof David Jamieson Dr Maurizio Toscano Prof Rachel Webster This course develops an interdisciplinary understanding of the social, political, economic and scientific perspectives on climate change. University of Melbourne'),(229,'Generating the Wealth of Nations',NULL,NULL,'Coursera','Economics & Finance',' Generating the Wealth of Nations Coursera Economics & Finance Professor Jeff Borland A survey of the history of economic development in the world in the past 300 years. University of Melbourne'),(230,'Exercise Physiology: Understanding the Athlete Within',NULL,NULL,'Coursera','Medicine',' Exercise Physiology: Understanding the Athlete Within Coursera Medicine Professor Mark Hargreaves Learn about the physiological responses to acute and chronic exercise and their relevance for athletic performance. University of Melbourne'),(231,'Passion Driven Statistics',NULL,NULL,'Coursera','Statistics, Data Analysis, and Scientific Computing',' Passion Driven Statistics Coursera Statistics, Data Analysis, and Scientific Computing Lisa Dierker With existing data, you will develop skills in data analysis and basic statistics by exploring your own research question. Wesleyan University'),(232,'Introduction to Pharmacy',NULL,NULL,'Coursera','Medicine',' Introduction to Pharmacy Coursera Medicine Kenneth M. Hale This course is a survey of the profession of pharmacy including its history, evolving scope of practice, ethical foundations, regulation, educational and career opportunities, and more. We will also explore topics relating to medication use and drug development. Ohio State University'),(233,'Principles of Public Health',NULL,NULL,'Coursera','Medicine',' Principles of Public Health Coursera Medicine Zuzana Bic Principles of Public Health introduces the major concepts and principles of public health and the determinants of health status in communities. Emphasizes the ecological model that focuses on the linkages and relationships among multiple natural and social determinants affecting health. University of California, Irvine'),(234,'Generation Rx: The Science Behind Prescription Drug Abuse',NULL,NULL,'Coursera','Medicine',' Generation Rx: The Science Behind Prescription Drug Abuse Coursera Medicine Nicole Cartwright Kwiek Think that a prescription medication must be safer than a â€œstreet drugâ€? Think again. Investigate the epidemic rise of prescription drug abuse and use science to debunk commonly held misconceptions regarding this phenomenon. Ohio State University'),(235,'The Ancient Greeks',NULL,NULL,'Coursera','Humanities and Social Sciences',' The Ancient Greeks Coursera Humanities and Social Sciences Andrew Szegedy-Maszak This is a survey of ancient Greek history from the Bronze Age to the death of Socrates in 399 BCE. Along with studying the most important events and personalities, we will consider broader issues such as political and cultural values and methods of historical interpretation.  Wesleyan University'),(236,'Modern European Mysticism and Psychological Thought',NULL,NULL,'Coursera','Humanities and Social Sciences',' Modern European Mysticism and Psychological Thought Coursera Humanities and Social Sciences Jonathan Garb The course will examine the psychological thought of the modern mystical traditions in Europe. We shall focus on two topics with wider cultural implications: The soul and the heart.  Hebrew University of Jerusalem'),(237,'Synapses, Neurons and Brains ',NULL,NULL,'Coursera','Biology & Life Sciences',' Synapses, Neurons and Brains  Coursera Biology & Life Sciences Idan Segev You will become intimately acquainted with the operational principles of neuronal â€œlife-wareâ€ (synapses, neurons and the networks that they form) as well as with recent ideas about how the dynamics of these networks generate the â€œneuronal code.â€  As an aperitif we will highlight present brain-excitements and for dessert we will discuss the future of brain research\n Hebrew University of Jerusalem'),(238,'Coding the Matrix: Linear Algebra through Computer Science Applications',NULL,NULL,'Coursera','Computer Science: Theory',' Coding the Matrix: Linear Algebra through Computer Science Applications Coursera Computer Science: Theory Phil Klein Learn the concepts and methods of linear algebra, and how to use them to think about computational problems arising in computer science.  Coursework includes building on the concepts to write small programs and run them on real data.  Brown University'),(239,'Introduction to Digital Sound Design',NULL,NULL,'Coursera','Music, Film, and Audio Engineering',' Introduction to Digital Sound Design Coursera Music, Film, and Audio Engineering Steve Everett Sounds and music are embedded in almost every aspect of daily life. This course will provide an overview of the fundamental principles of sound and the factors that determine our audio perception. It will also explore techniques of recording, mixing, processing, synthesis, sampling, analysis, and editing of digital audio. Emory University'),(240,'Immigration and U.S. Citizenship',NULL,NULL,'Coursera','Humanities and Social Sciences',' Immigration and U.S. Citizenship Coursera Humanities and Social Sciences Polly Price What does it mean for an immigrant to become a U.S. citizen? Through a background of historical and policy perspectives, this course will examine U.S. law governing how citizenship is acquired, the constitutional and international law foundations underlying immigration regulation, the role of the federal government in regulating immigration, and immigration law reform.   Emory University'),(241,'AIDS',NULL,NULL,'Coursera','Medicine',' AIDS Coursera Medicine Kimberley Sessions Hagen This course will discuss HIV/AIDS in the US and around the world including its history, science, and culture as well as recent developments in prevention education, biomedical research, vaccine development, HIV testing, and current treatments. The course will also include a review of past, present, and potential future controversies surrounding HIV/AIDS. Emory University'),(242,'The Language of Hollywood: Storytelling, Sound, and Color',NULL,NULL,'Coursera','Humanities and Social Sciences',' The Language of Hollywood: Storytelling, Sound, and Color Coursera Humanities and Social Sciences Scott Higgins This Film History course explores how fundamental changes in film technology affected popular Hollywood storytelling. We will consider the transition to sound, and the introduction of color. Wesleyan University'),(243,'The Fiction of Relationship',NULL,NULL,'Coursera','Humanities and Social Sciences',' The Fiction of Relationship Coursera Humanities and Social Sciences Arnold Weinstein What is the nature of our relationship to others and the world?  How can literature help us see these relationships more clearly? This course seeks to explore such questions through adventurous readings of ten great works of narrative fiction from the 18th to the 20th century. Brown University'),(244,'Science from Superheroes to Global Warming',NULL,NULL,'Coursera','Physical & Earth Sciences',' Science from Superheroes to Global Warming Coursera Physical & Earth Sciences Michael Dennin Explore how science works and what constitutes \"good\" science through case studies drawn from a wide spectrum of people\'s experience, for example superheros, movies, and real world issues such as global warming.  University of California, Irvine'),(245,'Useful Genetics',NULL,NULL,'Coursera','Biology & Life Sciences',' Useful Genetics Coursera Biology & Life Sciences Rosemary Redfield This course will give you a thorough understanding of gene function and inheritance, and will enable you to apply this understanding to real-world issues, both personal and societal. The University of British Columbia'),(246,'Archaeology\'s Dirty Little Secrets',NULL,NULL,'Coursera','Humanities and Social Sciences',' Archaeology\'s Dirty Little Secrets Coursera Humanities and Social Sciences Susan E. Alcock Admit it â€” you wanted to be an archaeologist when you grew up...  This course builds on that enthusiasm, while radically expanding your notions about just what archaeology is and just what archaeologists do. \n  Brown University'),(247,'Algebra',NULL,NULL,'Coursera','Mathematics',' Algebra Coursera Mathematics Sarah Eichhorn, Ph.D. Rachel Cohen Lehman, Ph.D. This course is taught so that students will acquire a solid foundation in algebra. The course concentrates on the various functions that are important to the study of calculus. University of California, Irvine'),(248,'Pre-Calculus',NULL,NULL,'Coursera','Mathematics',' Pre-Calculus Coursera Mathematics Sarah Eichhorn, Ph.D. Rachel Cohen Lehman, Ph.D. This class prepares students for eligibility to enroll in the first semester of single variable calculus. University of California, Irvine'),(249,'Introduction to Biology: DNA to Organisms',NULL,NULL,'Coursera','Biology & Life Sciences',' Introduction to Biology: DNA to Organisms Coursera Biology & Life Sciences Diane O\'Dowd Adrienne Williams Through this class you should be able to explain basic concepts in cellular and molecular biology using correct terminology, as well as develop critical thinking and problem-solving skills that can be applied to all of your studies of biology. University of California, Irvine'),(250,'Science, Technology, and Society in China I: Basic Concepts',NULL,